{"title_page": "Rick Santelli", "text_new": "{{short description|CNBC commentator}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Rick Santelli\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|birth_name  = Rick John Santelli\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1956|7|6}}<ref name=\"chicagotribune1\" /><ref>https://talkingbiznews.com/2/talking-biz-news-today-july-6-2018/</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n|education   = [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]], [[economics]]\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|occupation  = [[CNBC]] [[Pundit (expert)|commentator]], [[Derivative (finance)|derivatives]] [[Trader (finance)|trader]]\n|spouse      =\n|children    =\n|Web site    =\n|salary      =\n}}\n\n'''Rick John Santelli''' (born July 6, 1956) is an editor for the [[CNBC]] Business News network.<ref name=\"santellibio\" /> He joined CNBC as an on-air editor on June 14, 1999, reporting primarily from the floor of the [[Chicago Board of Trade]]. He was formerly the vice president for an institutional trading and [[hedge fund]] account for futures-related products.  He is also credited as being a catalyst in the early formation of the [[Tea Party movement]] via a statement he made on February 19, 2009.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/id/2274224/pagenum/2 Fed-Bashing Three Ways] ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', Bethany McLean. November 9, 2010</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThe grandson of four [[Italian people|Italian]] immigrants, Rick John Santelli<ref name=Illio>{{citation|url=http://libsysdigi.library.illinois.edu/OCA/Books2012-12/illio/illio197683univ/illio197683univ.pdf|pages=375, 397|title=The Illio|year=1976|issue=83|publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign}}</ref> was born near Taylor Street in [[Chicago]]'s old Italian neighborhood and moved with his family to [[Lombard, Illinois]] at age six.<ref name=\"best 5\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921110507/http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/2723474,CST-NWS-TeaParty19.article|archivedate=September 21, 2010|title='Best 5 minutes of my life'|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/2723474,CST-NWS-TeaParty19.article|last=Pallasch|first=Abdon M.|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 19, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> After graduating from [[Willowbrook High School]] in [[Villa Park, Illinois]], Santelli attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]], where he was a member of the Ku Klux Klan and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[economics]] in 1979.<ref name=Illio /><ref name=\"santellibio\" /><ref name=\"best 5\" /><ref name=\"no teleprompter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thinkadvisor.com/2009/06/01/no-teleprompter-needed-cnbcs-rick-santelli/?slreturn=20180815002137|title=No Teleprompter Needed: CNBC's Rick Santelli|work=Research Magazine|date=June 2009|last=Rusoff|first=Jane Wollman|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Financial===\nIn 1979, he joined the [[Chicago Mercantile Exchange]] and the Chicago Board of Trade as a commodity trader and order filler for [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]]; he eventually became the Vice President of [[Interest rate future|Interest Rate Futures and Options]].<ref name=\"santellibio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/rick-santelli/ |title=Rick Santelli|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nIn the 1990s, Santelli felt that the financial industry was changing in a way \"not beneficial to me and my family\",<ref name=\"fivequestions\">{{cite news|last=Ahrens |first=Frank |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/economy-watch/2008/11/five_questions_for_cnbcs_rick.html |title=Five questions for CNBC's Rick Santelli |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date=2008-11-23 |accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> and accepted a full-time job with [[CNBC]] in 1999.<ref name=\"santellibio\"/>\n\n==Political and economic views==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2013}}\n\n===\"Chicago Tea Party\" remarks===\nSantelli drew attention for his remarks made on February 19, 2009, about the [[Homeowners Affordability and Stability Plan]], which was announced on February 18. While broadcasting from the floor of the [[CME Group|Chicago Mercantile Exchange]], Santelli accused the government of \"promoting bad behavior\", and raised the possibility of a \"Chicago Tea Party\". He suggested that individuals who knowingly obtained high-risk mortgages (and faced impending foreclosure as a consequence) were \"losers\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Etheridge|first=Eric|title=Rick Santelli: Tea Party Time|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/02/20/rick-santelli-tea-party-time/|newspaper=New York Times: Opinionator|date=February 20, 2009}}</ref> The [[Boston Tea Party|Tea Party]] remark was credited by some as \"igniting\" the [[Tea Party movement]] as a national phenomenon.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pallasch|first=Abdon M.|title='Best 5 minutes of my life'; His '09 CNBC rant against mortgage bailouts for 'losers' ignited the Tea Party movement|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 19, 2010|page=A4}}</ref><ref name=Krugman />\n\n====Responses====\n\nSantelli later clarified his comments and addressed concerns that the event was staged.<ref name=\"santelliarticle\">{{cite web|last=Santelli |first=Rick |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29471026 |title=Rick Santelli: I Want to Set the Record Straight |publisher=cnbc.com |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"ap_santelli\">{{cite web|last=Bauder |first=David |url=http://bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view/2009_03_02_CNBC:_Rick_Santelli_not_tied_to_political_Web_site |title=CNBC: Santelli not tied to political Web site |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2012-04-27}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2009, Santelli participated as a panel member in an Economic Leadership Forum hosted by the [[George Bush Presidential Library]] Foundation at [[Texas A&M University]].<ref name=\"texasAM\">{{cite web |url=http://tamunews.tamu.edu/archives/article.php?articleid=7557&month=4&year=2009 |title=Bush To Host Economic Leadership Forum  |publisher=tamunews.tamu.edu |date=2009-04-09 |accessdate=2009-09-26}}</ref>\n\n[[CNN.com]] reported that some compared Santelli to fictional reporter [[Howard Beale (Network)|Howard Beale]], the protagonist of the 1976 [[satire|satirical]] film ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]''.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/15/tea.parties/ Nationwide 'tea party' protests blast spending]. By Ashley Fantz. [[CNN.com]] Published April 15, 2009.</ref> Santelli said:\n{{quote|I think that this tea party phenomenon is steeped in American culture and steeped in the American notion to get involved with what's going on with our government. I haven't organized. I'm going to have to work to pay my taxes, so I'm not going to be able to get away today. But, I have to tell you \u2013 I'm pretty proud of this.<ref name=fox>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0409/21275.html Fox teas up a tempest]. By Michael Calderone. ''[[The Politico]]''. Published April 15, 2009.</ref>}}\n\nSantelli's comments also garnered praise from [[Libertarianism|libertarians]]. Mark R. Crovelli wrote:\n\n{{quote|In the world of financial \"journalism,\" CNBC's Rick Santelli stands out as a refreshing and intelligent antidote to the hordes of perma-bulls, fed apologists, and chart sorcerers that otherwise pollute the financial airwaves ... The trouble with Santelli, however, is that his political and economic philosophy is inconsistent and incomplete, and does not offer a viable alternative to that being peddled by his Keynesian opponents.<ref>{{cite web|last=Crovelli|first=Mark R.|title=The Trouble With Rick Santelli|url=http://www.lewrockwell.com/2011/03/mark-r-crovelli/the-trouble-with-rick-santelli/|publisher=[[LewRockwell.com]]}}</ref>}}\n\nSantelli has also been criticized by the left; for example, [[George Monbiot]] said \"it is the most alarming example of cheap demagoguery you are likely to have seen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monbiot.com/2010/06/14/bogus-misdirected-and-effective/ |title=Bogus, Misdirected and Effective|last1=Monbiot|first1=George |accessdate=2013-12-12|date=2012-06-14}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said:\n{{quote|... Somehow, [the Republican Party] has become infected by an almost pathological meanspiritedness, a contempt for what CNBC's Rick Santelli, in the famous rant that launched the Tea Party, called \"losers.\" If you're an American, and you're down on your luck, these people don't want to help; they want to give you an extra kick...<ref name=Krugman>{{cite news|last=Krugman|first=Paul|title=Hunger Games, USA|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/15/opinion/krugman-hunger-games-usa.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n===COVID-19 virus remarks===\n\nOn March 5, 2020, Santelli made headlines for stating, after a series of stock declines driven by fears of a [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 virus pandemic]], that \"maybe we\u2019d be just better off if we gave [the virus] to everybody, and then in a month it would be over because the mortality rate of [COVID-19] probably isn\u2019t going to be any different if we did it that way than [in] the long-term picture, but the difference is we\u2019re wreaking havoc on global and domestic economies.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Murphy |title=CNBC\u2019s Rick Santelli suggests giving everyone coronavirus to spare the economy |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/cnbcs-rick-santelli-suggests-giving-everyone-coronavirus-to-spare-the-economy-2020-03-05 |work=[[MarketWatch]] |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>  This analysis was viewed as especially uninformed and dangerous, as a key concern at the time was that a concentrated outbreak - the exact event Santelli was suggesting society should embrace - would lead to an overwhelmed medical system and greatly increase the number of deaths from the virus due to the number of patients needing care exceeding the availability of medical assistance.<ref>{{cite news |first=Justin |last=Fox |title=How Bad Is the Coronavirus? Let\u2019s Run the Numbers |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-05/how-bad-is-the-coronavirus-let-s-compare-with-sars-ebola-flu |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 2015, Santelli has lived with his wife in [[Wayne, Illinois]].<ref name=\"chicagotribune1\">{{cite news|last=Rosenthal |first=Phil |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-rosenthal-23-feb23,0,6124753.story |title=Rant raises profile of CNBC on-air personality Rick Santelli |work=Chicago Tribune |date=2009-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225173408/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-rosenthal-23-feb23,0,6124753.story|archivedate=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/classified/realestate/elitestreet/ct-rick-santelli-elite-street-1029-biz-20151028-story.html|title=Rick Santelli of CNBC buys house in west suburban Wayne |last=Goldsborough|first=Bob|work=Chicago Tribune|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/15837966/ Rick Santelli bio on CNBC.com]\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/15840232?video=1039849853 Original speech by Rick Santelli on CNBC.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090316153711/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-santelli-cnbc-video,0,4962596.htmlstory Santelli's speech and White House response]\n\n{{Tea Party movement}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santelli, Rick}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American business and financial journalists]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Drexel Burnham Lambert]]\n[[Category:People from Wheaton, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:CNBC people]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Lombard, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|CNBC commentator}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Rick Santelli\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|birth_name  = Rick John Santelli\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1956|7|6}}<ref name=\"chicagotribune1\" /><ref>https://talkingbiznews.com/2/talking-biz-news-today-july-6-2018/</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n|education   = [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]], [[economics]]\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|occupation  = [[CNBC]] [[Pundit (expert)|commentator]], [[Derivative (finance)|derivatives]] [[Trader (finance)|trader]]\n|spouse      =\n|children    =\n|Web site    =\n|salary      =\n}}\n\n'''Rick John Santelli''' (born July 6, 1956) is an editor for the [[CNBC]] Business News network.<ref name=\"santellibio\" /> He joined CNBC as an on-air editor on June 14, 1999, reporting primarily from the floor of the [[Chicago Board of Trade]]. He was formerly the vice president for an institutional trading and [[hedge fund]] account for futures-related products.  He is also credited as being a catalyst in the early formation of the [[Tea Party movement]] via a statement he made on February 19, 2009.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/id/2274224/pagenum/2 Fed-Bashing Three Ways] ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', Bethany McLean. November 9, 2010</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThe grandson of four [[Italian people|Italian]] immigrants, Rick John Santelli<ref name=Illio>{{citation|url=http://libsysdigi.library.illinois.edu/OCA/Books2012-12/illio/illio197683univ/illio197683univ.pdf|pages=375, 397|title=The Illio|year=1976|issue=83|publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign}}</ref> was born near Taylor Street in [[Chicago]]'s old Italian neighborhood and moved with his family to [[Lombard, Illinois]] at age six.<ref name=\"best 5\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921110507/http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/2723474,CST-NWS-TeaParty19.article|archivedate=September 21, 2010|title='Best 5 minutes of my life'|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/2723474,CST-NWS-TeaParty19.article|last=Pallasch|first=Abdon M.|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 19, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> After graduating from [[Willowbrook High School]] in [[Villa Park, Illinois]], Santelli attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]], where he was a member of the [[Alpha Sigma Phi]] fraternity and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[economics]] in 1979.<ref name=Illio /><ref name=\"santellibio\" /><ref name=\"best 5\" /><ref name=\"no teleprompter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thinkadvisor.com/2009/06/01/no-teleprompter-needed-cnbcs-rick-santelli/?slreturn=20180815002137|title=No Teleprompter Needed: CNBC's Rick Santelli|work=Research Magazine|date=June 2009|last=Rusoff|first=Jane Wollman|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Financial===\nIn 1979, he joined the [[Chicago Mercantile Exchange]] and the Chicago Board of Trade as a commodity trader and order filler for [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]]; he eventually became the Vice President of [[Interest rate future|Interest Rate Futures and Options]].<ref name=\"santellibio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/rick-santelli/ |title=Rick Santelli|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nIn the 1990s, Santelli felt that the financial industry was changing in a way \"not beneficial to me and my family\",<ref name=\"fivequestions\">{{cite news|last=Ahrens |first=Frank |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/economy-watch/2008/11/five_questions_for_cnbcs_rick.html |title=Five questions for CNBC's Rick Santelli |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date=2008-11-23 |accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> and accepted a full-time job with [[CNBC]] in 1999.<ref name=\"santellibio\"/>\n\n==Political and economic views==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2013}}\n\n===\"Chicago Tea Party\" remarks===\nSantelli drew attention for his remarks made on February 19, 2009, about the [[Homeowners Affordability and Stability Plan]], which was announced on February 18. While broadcasting from the floor of the [[CME Group|Chicago Mercantile Exchange]], Santelli accused the government of \"promoting bad behavior\", and raised the possibility of a \"Chicago Tea Party\". He suggested that individuals who knowingly obtained high-risk mortgages (and faced impending foreclosure as a consequence) were \"losers\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Etheridge|first=Eric|title=Rick Santelli: Tea Party Time|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/02/20/rick-santelli-tea-party-time/|newspaper=New York Times: Opinionator|date=February 20, 2009}}</ref> The [[Boston Tea Party|Tea Party]] remark was credited by some as \"igniting\" the [[Tea Party movement]] as a national phenomenon.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pallasch|first=Abdon M.|title='Best 5 minutes of my life'; His '09 CNBC rant against mortgage bailouts for 'losers' ignited the Tea Party movement|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 19, 2010|page=A4}}</ref><ref name=Krugman />\n\n====Responses====\n\nSantelli later clarified his comments and addressed concerns that the event was staged.<ref name=\"santelliarticle\">{{cite web|last=Santelli |first=Rick |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29471026 |title=Rick Santelli: I Want to Set the Record Straight |publisher=cnbc.com |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"ap_santelli\">{{cite web|last=Bauder |first=David |url=http://bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/view/2009_03_02_CNBC:_Rick_Santelli_not_tied_to_political_Web_site |title=CNBC: Santelli not tied to political Web site |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2012-04-27}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2009, Santelli participated as a panel member in an Economic Leadership Forum hosted by the [[George Bush Presidential Library]] Foundation at [[Texas A&M University]].<ref name=\"texasAM\">{{cite web |url=http://tamunews.tamu.edu/archives/article.php?articleid=7557&month=4&year=2009 |title=Bush To Host Economic Leadership Forum  |publisher=tamunews.tamu.edu |date=2009-04-09 |accessdate=2009-09-26}}</ref>\n\n[[CNN.com]] reported that some compared Santelli to fictional reporter [[Howard Beale (Network)|Howard Beale]], the protagonist of the 1976 [[satire|satirical]] film ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]''.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/15/tea.parties/ Nationwide 'tea party' protests blast spending]. By Ashley Fantz. [[CNN.com]] Published April 15, 2009.</ref> Santelli said:\n{{quote|I think that this tea party phenomenon is steeped in American culture and steeped in the American notion to get involved with what's going on with our government. I haven't organized. I'm going to have to work to pay my taxes, so I'm not going to be able to get away today. But, I have to tell you \u2013 I'm pretty proud of this.<ref name=fox>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0409/21275.html Fox teas up a tempest]. By Michael Calderone. ''[[The Politico]]''. Published April 15, 2009.</ref>}}\n\nSantelli's comments also garnered praise from [[Libertarianism|libertarians]]. Mark R. Crovelli wrote:\n\n{{quote|In the world of financial \"journalism,\" CNBC's Rick Santelli stands out as a refreshing and intelligent antidote to the hordes of perma-bulls, fed apologists, and chart sorcerers that otherwise pollute the financial airwaves ... The trouble with Santelli, however, is that his political and economic philosophy is inconsistent and incomplete, and does not offer a viable alternative to that being peddled by his Keynesian opponents.<ref>{{cite web|last=Crovelli|first=Mark R.|title=The Trouble With Rick Santelli|url=http://www.lewrockwell.com/2011/03/mark-r-crovelli/the-trouble-with-rick-santelli/|publisher=[[LewRockwell.com]]}}</ref>}}\n\nSantelli has also been criticized by the left; for example, [[George Monbiot]] said \"it is the most alarming example of cheap demagoguery you are likely to have seen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monbiot.com/2010/06/14/bogus-misdirected-and-effective/ |title=Bogus, Misdirected and Effective|last1=Monbiot|first1=George |accessdate=2013-12-12|date=2012-06-14}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said:\n{{quote|... Somehow, [the Republican Party] has become infected by an almost pathological meanspiritedness, a contempt for what CNBC's Rick Santelli, in the famous rant that launched the Tea Party, called \"losers.\" If you're an American, and you're down on your luck, these people don't want to help; they want to give you an extra kick...<ref name=Krugman>{{cite news|last=Krugman|first=Paul|title=Hunger Games, USA|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/15/opinion/krugman-hunger-games-usa.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n===COVID-19 virus remarks===\n\nOn March 5, 2020, Santelli made headlines for stating, after a series of stock declines driven by fears of a [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 virus pandemic]], that \"maybe we\u2019d be just better off if we gave [the virus] to everybody, and then in a month it would be over because the mortality rate of [COVID-19] probably isn\u2019t going to be any different if we did it that way than [in] the long-term picture, but the difference is we\u2019re wreaking havoc on global and domestic economies.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Murphy |title=CNBC\u2019s Rick Santelli suggests giving everyone coronavirus to spare the economy |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/cnbcs-rick-santelli-suggests-giving-everyone-coronavirus-to-spare-the-economy-2020-03-05 |work=[[MarketWatch]] |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>  This analysis was viewed as especially uninformed and dangerous, as a key concern at the time was that a concentrated outbreak - the exact event Santelli was suggesting society should embrace - would lead to an overwhelmed medical system and greatly increase the number of deaths from the virus due to the number of patients needing care exceeding the availability of medical assistance.<ref>{{cite news |first=Justin |last=Fox |title=How Bad Is the Coronavirus? Let\u2019s Run the Numbers |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-05/how-bad-is-the-coronavirus-let-s-compare-with-sars-ebola-flu |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 2015, Santelli has lived with his wife in [[Wayne, Illinois]].<ref name=\"chicagotribune1\">{{cite news|last=Rosenthal |first=Phil |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-rosenthal-23-feb23,0,6124753.story |title=Rant raises profile of CNBC on-air personality Rick Santelli |work=Chicago Tribune |date=2009-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225173408/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-rosenthal-23-feb23,0,6124753.story|archivedate=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/classified/realestate/elitestreet/ct-rick-santelli-elite-street-1029-biz-20151028-story.html|title=Rick Santelli of CNBC buys house in west suburban Wayne |last=Goldsborough|first=Bob|work=Chicago Tribune|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/15837966/ Rick Santelli bio on CNBC.com]\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/15840232?video=1039849853 Original speech by Rick Santelli on CNBC.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090316153711/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-santelli-cnbc-video,0,4962596.htmlstory Santelli's speech and White House response]\n\n{{Tea Party movement}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santelli, Rick}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American business and financial journalists]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Drexel Burnham Lambert]]\n[[Category:People from Wheaton, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:CNBC people]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Lombard, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "2601:282:680:a4d0:e45a:3449:fa5b:139e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Santelli"}
{"title_page": "Chloe x Halle", "text_new": "{{redirect|jrobertson2003|the actress|ig@jrobertson2003 }}\n{{short description|American contemporary R&B duo}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = jamauri x robertson\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Chloe x Halle Logo.svg\n| alt              = Chloe & Halle\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, Guitar and Piano\n| years_active     = {{start date|2013}}\u2013{{end date|present}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Parkwood Entertainment|Parkwood]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| associated_acts  =\n| website          = {{URL|chloexhalle.com}}\n| current_members  = Chloe Bailey <br> Halle Bailey\n}}\n\n'''Chloe x Halle''' is an American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] duo composed of sisters '''Chloe''' and '''Halle Bailey'''.\n\n==Origins==\n\nChloe and Halle Bailey were born in [[Atlanta]], Georgia, and raised in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/chloe-x-halle-mn0003000052/biography|title=Chloe x Halle Biography|first= Andy | last=Kellman|publisher=[[AllMusic.com]]|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> They first performed as Chloe x Halle by posting covers of pop songs on [[YouTube]]. They launched their [[YouTube]] channel at the ages of 10 and 11, respectively, with a cover of Beyonc\u00e9's \u201cBest Thing I Never Had\u201d. Their rendition  of \u201cPretty Hurts\u201d by [[Beyonc\u00e9]] went viral and drew the attention of the singer herself and in 2015, she signed the sister duo to her management company, [[Parkwood Entertainment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.co.uk/entertainment/news/a35443/beyonce-signs-youtube-chloe-halle/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 signs Youtube stars Chloe and Halle|last=Scott|first=Ellen|date=2015-05-02|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\nChloe x Halle's debut EP, ''[[Sugar Symphony]]'', was released April 29, 2016. The EP was accompanied by its singles \"Drop\" and \"Fall\". Later in 2016, they made cameo appearances in Beyonc\u00e9's ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'' visual album.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/04/24/were-going-nuts-over-all-of-the-cameos-in-beyonces-lemonade-5838344/|title=We're going nuts over all of the cameos in Beyonce's Lemonade|date=April 24, 2016|work=Metro|access-date=October 26, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> They later served as Beyonc\u00e9's opening act for the European leg of [[The Formation World Tour]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.etonline.com/news/191957_exclusive_chloe_x_halle_reveal_they_are_opening_for_the_european_leg_of_beyonces_formation_tour|title=EXCLUSIVE: Chloe x Halle Reveal They Are Opening for the European Leg of Beyonce's Formation Tour!|work=Entertainment Tonight|access-date=October 26, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2017, Chloe x Halle released their critically acclaimed project, ''The Two of Us'', which featured new music mostly written and produced by the duo. The mixtape was featured on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's Best R&B Albums of 2017 list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/20-best-rb-albums-of-2017-202901/chloe-x-halle-the-two-of-us-122568/|title=20 Best R&B Albums of 2017|last1=Spanos|first1=Brittany|first2=Suzy|last2=Exposito|first3=Mosi| last3=Reeves|first4=Simon|last4=Vozick-Levinson|first5=Maura|last5=Johnston|first6=Joe|last6= Levy|first7=Michelle| last7=Ofiwe|date=December 20, 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=October 26, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Chloe x Halle released the theme song for the TV series ''[[Grown-ish]]'', entitled \"Grown\". They were added to the cast as series regulars, after initially signing on for recurring roles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8475879/chloe-and-halle-bailey-grown-ish-season-2-regulars|title='Grown-ish' Season 2 Adds Chloe x Halle as Series Regulars|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Their song \"The Kids Are Alright\" was featured in the series debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/video/chloe-x-halle-grownish-premiere/|title=Chloe x Halle Release New Song During 'Grown-ish' Premiere|work=[[TigerBeat]]|language=en-US|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, 2018, the duo released their debut album, ''[[The Kids Are Alright (Chloe x Halle album)|The Kids Are Alright]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8211607/chloe-x-halle-announce-album-the-kids-are-alright-reveal|title=Chloe x Halle Announce Debut Album 'The Kids Are Alright,' Reveal Cover Art: Exclusive|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Later, the album and Chloe x Halle were nominated for two [[Grammy Award]]s, \"[[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]]\" and \"[[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\", respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/chloe-x-halle|title=Chloe x Halle|date=2018-05-12|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n\"Our debut album ''The Kids Are Alright'' means so much to us, it's three years of self-discovery, vulnerability, and growth, all put into one album. We've put our hearts and souls into every lyric, every beat, and we cannot wait for the world to hear.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chloexhalle.com/about/|title=Chloe x Halle {{!}} Official Website|last=Conte|first=Columbia Records, Sony Music Entertainment, HJ|website=www.chloexhalle.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2018, it was announced that they would be the opening act for the U.S. leg of Beyonce and [[Jay-Z]]'s [[On the Run II Tour]], alongside [[DJ Khaled]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8458740/chloe-x-halle-dj-khaled-beyonce-jay-z-tour-openers|title=Chloe x Halle & DJ Khaled Announced as Openers for Beyonce & JAY-Z's On the Run II Tour|work=Billboard|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2019, at a special performance at the [[Fonda Theatre]], the duo announced that their sophomore album is titled \u201cUngodly Hour.\u201d They also performed 2 new songs from their new album named \u201cDo It,\u201d and \u201cRest of Your Life.\u201d\n\n== Artistry ==\nChloe x Halle write and arrange all of their songs in their home studio. They also play their own instruments.\n\nHalle considers herself a \u201cjazz-head\u201d and has been listening to [[Billie Holiday]] since she was five years old. She has cited the singer as one of the major influences on her vocals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-chloe-x-halle-caught-beyonces-ear-83687/|title=How Chloe x Halle Caught Beyonce's Ear|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|last2=Spanos|first2=Brittany|date=2016-06-23|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\nChloe is inspired by [[Alternative rock|Alternative]] artists such as [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]] and [[Bj\u00f6rk]] and loves [[R&B]] music.<ref>{{Citation|last=NQ Social|title=Chloe and Halle talks their Individual Artistic Style|date=2017-11-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UUNpVIKDE4s|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=BUILD Series|title=Chloe x Halle Chat About \"Grown-ish\"|date=2017-11-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qSdt2FhvmyM|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\nThe duo considers their sound as a combination of their music taste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rickeysmileymorningshow.com/1874091/chloe-x-halle-grownish-original-sound/|title=Chloe X Halle On How Their Music Tastes Combine In Their Work [EXCLUSIVE VIDEO]|date=2018-03-02|website=The Rickey Smiley Morning Show|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n\u201cMy sister and I like to make music that has interesting sounds and nuances.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/porter/article-5b0e9640b1965a43/lifestyle/culture|title=Everything you need to know about Chloe X Halle|last=Net-A-Porter|website=NET-A-PORTER|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nOn February 3, 2019, Chloe x Halle sang \"[[America the Beautiful]]\" at [[Super Bowl LIII]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gladys Knight Sings Super Bowl National Anthem|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/gladys-knight-chloe-x-halle-open-super-bowl-2019|work=[[The Recording Academy]]|date=February 3, 2019|accessdate=February 3, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Disney announced that Halle Bailey had been cast as [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] in the upcoming live-action remake of ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'', set to be directed by [[Rob Marshall]]. The film is to be released sometime in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disney-finds-little-mermaid-star-singer-halle-bailey-1220951|title=Disney Finds 'Little Mermaid' Star in Singer Halle Bailey|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 3, 2019|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> Halle's casting created a small controversy on social media, with some claiming the character of Ariel, a fictional mermaid, could not be African American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/08/07/halle-bailey-opens-up-little-mermaid-casting-backlash/1941300001/|title=Halle Bailey breaks her silence on 'Little Mermaid' casting backlash: 'I don't pay attention to the negativity'|last=Yasharoff|first=Hannah|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> However, the reactions to the diverse casting choice has been mostly positive.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of compilation albums, with selected chart positions and details\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chloe-x-halle/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Chloe x Halle Chart History (Billboard 200)|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[R&B Albums|US<br>R&B]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/chloe-x-halle/chart-history/r-and-b-albums|title=Chloe x Halle Chart History (Top R&B Albums)|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Kids Are Alright (Chloe x Halle album)|The Kids Are Alright]]''<ref>{{cite news|last=Braca|first=Nina|title=Chloe x Halle Announce Debut Album 'The Kids Are Alright,' Reveal Cover Art: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8211607/chloe-x-halle-announce-album-the-kids-are-alright-reveal|work=Billboard|date=February 21, 2018|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n|\n* Released : March 23, 2018\n* Label: [[Parkwood Entertainment|Parkwood]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* Format: [[CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Streaming music|streaming]]\n| 139 || 19\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Uncovered''\n|\n* Released: September 23, 2013\n* Label: ADED.US\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sugar Symphony]]''\n|\n* Released: April 29, 2016\n* Label: Parkwood, Columbia\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=